Place the @quinoa{120%g} into a #sieve{} and rinse it under running water for at least
~{30%seconds} (this will improve the flavour). Leave to one side.

> If you don't have a sieve don't worry!

Cut the @onion{1} in half through the root, peel and chop into roughly ½cm pieces.
Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one).
Remove the stalk and the core from the @green pepper{1} and chop it into ½cm squares.
Peel and chop the @carrot{1} into ½cm cubes. Roughly chop the @coriander{½%bunch}.
Drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1%400g can}.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #saucepan{} over a medium heat. Add your garlic and
onion. Gently fry for ~{3%minutes} or until soft. Add your pepper and carrot.
Gently fry for a further ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the @ground cumin{1%tsp},
@chilli powder{¾%tsp} and @ground cinnamon{½%tsp}. Stir to coat and gently fry
for ~{30%seconds}.

> Use a little less chilli powder if you prefer things less spicy!

Add the @water{300%ml} to the pan along with the @vegetable stock pot{½}.
Add your quinoa, kidney beans, @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} and
@tomato puree{2%tbsp}. Season with @salt{pinch} and a good grind of
@black pepper{} and stir everything together.

Bring your chilli to the boil and then reduce to a simmer. Cover with a #lid{} and
let your chilli cook for about ~{15-20%minutes} or until your quinoa is tender.

Zest the @lime{½} into the @sour cream{½%tsp} together with a pinch of @salt{pinch}
and a good grind of @black pepper{}.

Prepare a 'slurry': place the @cornflour{½%tbsp} into a #small bowl{} with the same
amount of @cold water{}. Whisk with a #fork{} until your cornflour is dissolved.

> A 'slurry' is a mixture that contains equal parts starch (in our case cornflour)
> and cold water. It's used to help thicken a sauce, soup or stew!

Add three-quarters of your coriander to your chilli stir through. Whisk your
slurry again and add it to your chilli, stirring continuously. Gently heat,
stir to combine and until slightly thickened (about ~{30%seconds} or so should
do it). Remove from the heat and serve in #bowls{} topped with some sour cream.
Sprinkle over some of your remaining coriander and tuck in!